<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>Heading elements (<code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> through <code>&lt;h6&gt;</code>) define the structure and hierarchy of your content. Vanilla Breeze applies consistent typography with <code>font-weight: 600</code>, tight line-height, and balanced text wrapping across all levels.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Heading Scale</h2>
    <p>Each level maps to a design token for consistent sizing:</p>

    <div class="example">
      <h1>Heading Level 1</h1>
      <h2>Heading Level 2</h2>
      <h3>Heading Level 3</h3>
      <h4>Heading Level 4</h4>
      <h5>Heading Level 5</h5>
      <h6>Heading Level 6</h6>
    </div>

    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Element</th>
          <th>Font Size Token</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h1&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>var(--font-size-4xl)</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h2&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>var(--font-size-3xl)</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h3&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>var(--font-size-2xl)</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h4&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>var(--font-size-xl)</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h5&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>var(--font-size-lg)</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h6&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>var(--font-size-md)</code> + <code>font-weight: 700</code></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Theme Ornament Tokens</h2>
    <p>Themes can add decorative glyphs before or after headings by setting CSS custom properties. This provides a standard hook so themes don't need to override <code>::before</code>/<code>::after</code> directly.</p>

    <h3>Global Tokens</h3>
    <p>Apply to all heading levels:</p>
    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Token</th>
          <th>Default</th>
          <th>Purpose</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--heading-ornament-before</code></td>
          <td><code>none</code></td>
          <td>Content before all headings</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--heading-ornament-after</code></td>
          <td><code>none</code></td>
          <td>Content after all headings</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Per-Level Tokens</h3>
    <p>Override specific heading levels (falls back to global token):</p>
    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Token</th>
          <th>Applies To</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--h1-ornament-before</code> / <code>--h1-ornament-after</code></td>
          <td><code>&lt;h1&gt;</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--h2-ornament-before</code> / <code>--h2-ornament-after</code></td>
          <td><code>&lt;h2&gt;</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--h3-ornament-before</code> / <code>--h3-ornament-after</code></td>
          <td><code>&lt;h3&gt;</code></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Theme Example</h3>
    <p>A theme could use these tokens to add decorative symbols:</p>
    <div class="example">
      <div style="--heading-ornament-before: '✦ '; --heading-ornament-after: ' ✦';">
        <h3>Decorated Heading</h3>
      </div>
      <div style="--h3-ornament-before: '§ ';">
        <h3>Section-Style Heading</h3>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Use headings in order (h1, then h2, then h3) — never skip levels</li>
      <li>Each page should have exactly one <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code></li>
      <li>Ornament content inserted via <code>::before</code>/<code>::after</code> is not read by most screen readers, which is the desired behavior for decorative glyphs</li>
      <li><code>text-wrap: balance</code> prevents awkward single-word last lines</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

